Philip Morris, Apple, Smithfield: Intellectual Property

-- B y   V i c t o r i a   S l i n d - F l o r
-- 
2011-05-27T11:01:01Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-27/philip-morris-apple-smithfield-pirate-bay-tata-intellectual-property.html
Philip Morris International Inc. (PM) , the
maker of Marlboro, Benson & Hedges and Virginia Slims
cigarettes, took a license to a patent on a nicotine-delivery
system intended to reduce the harm of smoking.  No financial terms were disclosed in a company statement.
New York-based  Philip Morris  seeks to commercialize the
technology covered by the patent, Doug Dean, senior vice
president for research and development, said in the statement.  Professor Jed Rose , who heads the  Duke University Center
for Nicotine and Smoking Cessation Research , was among the
inventors. Rose is also one of the developers of the nicotine
patch system used by people trying to quit smoking.  The technology licensed by Philip Morris “has the
potential over time to offer an attractive alternative to
conventional cigarettes, thereby reducing smokes’ exposure to
carcinogens and other harmful smoke constituents,” Rose said in
the statement.  Rose is a named inventor on  21 U.S. patents related to
smoking cessation , according to the database of the U.S. Patent
and Trademark Office.  Commerce Plans Export Regulation Overhaul to Boost Trade  The U.S. Commerce Department will simplify export
guidelines, streamline the patent award process and eliminate
outdated import restrictions as part of President Barack Obama’s
plan to cut unneeded regulations.  The department overhaul is aimed at reducing costs for
companies and individuals seeking to sell products abroad,
according to a White House report. Obama formed an Export
Council in March 2010 to help double U.S. exports to about $3.1
trillion by 2015 and support 2 million additional jobs.  Under the proposal, the State Department will simplify
regulations for exporters of defense products and services. The
Obama administration estimates that as many as 30,000 licenses
for basic defense articles that were handled by the department
last year under arms trafficking laws will be transferred to the
Commerce Department and governed by more flexible export rules,
according to the report.  Obama ordered a review of government departments on Jan.
18, saying he wanted “to remove outdated regulations that
stifle  job creation  and make our economy less competitive.” A
White House report released yesterday outlined plans for 30 U.S.
agencies to revise regulations.  “It’s pretty technical stuff, but the impact will be to
free up small businesses and large businesses to export goods to
other nations without facing nearly as much red tape and
bureaucratic barriers,” Cass Sunstein, director of the Office
of Information and Regulatory Affairs, said in an interview.  The proposals would “simplify and streamline”
requirements for businesses to gain export control approvals for
“low-risk” national security technology, he said.  The changes at the Commerce Department focus on the U.S.
Patent and Trademark Office, the Bureau of Industry and Security
and the International Trade Administration. The overhaul will
remove unnecessary technical complexity in some export-control
rules, streamline the process for individuals and companies to
get patents and withdraw obsolete import restrictions that
burden regulators, according to the report.  For more patent news, click here.  Trademark  ‘Rogue’ Websites Targeted in Bill Passed by Senate Panel  Legislation aimed at combating “rogue” websites that sell
pirated content won unanimous approval from a U.S. Senate panel
before being blocked by a senator opposed to certain provisions
in the bill.  The Senate Judiciary Committee passed the measure, called
the Protect IP Act, which targets websites “dedicated to
infringing activities,” including the sale of illegally copied
music, movies, pharmaceuticals and consumer products.  The measure, S.968, would allow the U.S. attorney general
to seek court orders requiring U.S.-based search engines to stop
providing links to infringing sites. Internet-service providers
also would be called on to block access to infringing sites, and
payment processors and online advertising networks would be
required to stop doing business with such sites.  “Copyright infringement and the sale of counterfeit goods
can cost American businesses billions of dollars, and result in
hundreds of thousands of lost jobs,” said Senator Patrick
Leahy, a Vermont Democrat who chairs the Senate Judiciary
Committee. Leahy introduced the bill May 12 with Republican
Senators Orrin Hatch of Utah and Chuck Grassley of Iowa.  Within hours of the committee’s vote, Senator  Ron Wyden , an
Oregon Democrat, said he would use a procedural move to block
the measure from reaching a vote in the full Senate, saying it
“takes an overreaching approach to policing the Internet.” In
December, Wyden placed a hold on a similar anti-piracy bill.  Google Inc. (GOOG) , which operates the world’s largest search
engine, said it has “real concerns” with the legislation.  “We support the goal of the bill but we have real concerns
about some provisions,” including the impact that blocking
access to websites would have on free expression, Google
spokeswoman Mistique Cano said in a statement.  “We look forward to working with Congress to make sure the
Protect IP Act can target sites dedicated to piracy while
protecting free expression and legitimate sites,” Cano said.  Google, Yahoo! Inc.,  EBay Inc. (EBAY) ,  Visa Inc. (V)  and  American
Express Co. (AXP)  sent a letter to Leahy and Grassley on May 25
objecting to a provision that would allow trademark or copyright
holders to take legal action against a domain name associated
with an infringing website. The companies said it would lead to
a “new litigation industry.”  The bill has the support of other business and trade
groups, including the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, the  Business
Software Alliance  and the  Motion Picture Association  of America.  The vote “serves as a wakeup call to those who illicitly
profit at the expense of American businesses and consumers,”
David Hirschmann, president of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce’s
 intellectual property  center, said in a statement. “The U.S.
will not tolerate your careless, reckless, malicious behavior.”  Apple Files, Dismisses Case Against Seller of White Phone Kits  Apple Inc. (AAPL) , maker of the iPhone and iPad, simultaneously
filed and dismissed a trademark-infringement lawsuit against a
Flushing,  New York , teenager who sold kits to convert an iPhone
into a white version.  The notice of dismissal gave no details of any settlement
between the parties. Fei Lik Lam was accused of selling
conversion kits through a website, www.whiteiphone4now.com
beginning in July 2010. Apple claimed he bought the panels,
marked with Apple trademarks, from an unauthorized seller in
 China ’s Shenzhen province.  In December,  CNN reported  that Apple co-founder Steve
Wozniak had read about the teenager’s business venture and
ordered a kit, which he used to convert his regular iPhone into
a white version.  Apple sent Lam a cease-and desist letter Dec. 1, and
afterward the website disappeared from the Internet, according
to the complaint filed May 25 in federal court in Brooklyn, New
York. Apple began selling authorized white phones April 28, the
company said in a statement.  In its complaint, Cupertino, California-based Apple asked
the court to order the seizure of all infringing materials and a
halt to future infringement, and to award money damages,
litigation costs and attorney fees.  Apple was represented by  John J. Kuster  and  James D. Arden 
of Chicago’s Sidley Austin LLP. No counsel for the defendant is
listed in the court file.  The case is Apple Inc., v. Fei Lik Lam, 1:11-cv-02507, U.S.
District Court, Eastern District of New York (Brooklyn).  Smithfield Sues Puerto Rico-Based Distributor for Infringement  Smithfield Foods Inc. (SFD) ’s Smithfield Packing unit sued a
Puerto Rico-based food distributor for trademark infringement.  In the lawsuit, filed May 25 in federal court in Norfolk,
Virginia, Smithfield alleged that  V. Suarez & Co.  of Guaynabo,
Puerto Rico, and its Packers Provision unit infringed the
“Shorgood” trademark used for chicken frankfurters.  According to court papers, Smithfield, the world’s largest
producer of pork products, has sold its line of chicken
frankfurters under the Shorgood name “for many years.” The
company said it originally used the mark through a license from
 ConAgra Foods Inc. (CAG)  of Omaha, Nebraska. One of its customers was
V. Suarez.  ConAgra said it would no longer use the Shorgood brand in
2005 and Smithfield filed an application to register the mark
with the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office in 2009, the company
said in its pleadings.  In April, Suarez informed Smithfield that it found an
alternative source of Shorgood-branded product, the Smithfield,
Virginia-based packing company claimed. Smithfield said Suarez
sold the products in identical packaging.  Smithfield said it is harmed by Suarez’s alleged use of
infringing packaging, and that consumers will falsely believe
there is an affiliation between Smithfield and the products.  It asked the court to tell Suarez to quit using the
Shorgood marks and to order the seizure of all products and
promotional materials bearing those marks. It also requested an
award of Suarez profits attributable to the alleged
infringement, together with money damages, and awards of
attorney fees and litigation costs.  Smithfield also asked for extra damages intended to punish
Suarez for its alleged infringement.  Suarez didn’t respond immediately to an e-mailed request
for comment.  Smithfield is represented by  Carl H. Pierce ,  Jeffrey A.
Porter  and  Brad R. Newberg  of Pittsburgh-based Reed Smith LLP.  The case is Smithfield Packing Co v. V. Suarez & Co., 2:11-
cv-00294, U.S. District Court, Eastern District of Virginia
(Norfolk).  For more trademark news, click here.  Copyright  Pirate Bay Sued in Finland in Bid to Halt Music Track Sharing  The Pirate Bay file-sharing website was sued in Finland by
a group of 23 Finnish record labels, which seek to prevent the
illegal distribution and downloading of copyrighted music in the
country.  The Finnish unit of the International Federation of the
Phonographic Industry filed the lawsuit at the Helsinki District
Court yesterday, according to a statement on its website. The
group asked the court to order telecommunications company  Elisa
Oyj (ELI1V)  to prevent customers from using the website.  Elisa said it opposes illegal distribution of copyrighted
content and plans to wait for the court to rule on the case,
according to an e-mailed statement from the Helsinki-based
company.
      Pirate Bay  is the largest file-sharing site using
BitTorrent software, which allows users to download and share
files for free. Pirate Bay has said the site is a network where
users put up content to share with other users and that there is
no copyrighted material on the site.  Its four founders were sentenced to one year in prison each
in April 2009 by a Swedish court. Three of the men had their
jail sentences reduced on appeal in November.  For more copyright news, click here.  Trade Secrets/Industrial Espionage  Tata’s Singur Land Deal ‘Trade Secrets’ to Be Disclosed  Details of a land deal between  Tata Motors Ltd. (TTMT)  and the
West Bengal Development Corp. previously kept from public view
as a trade secret may be revealed by an Indian government
minister, the Times of  India  reported.  The land in Singur in India’s West Bengal state, which was
to have been used to for an auto plant, will be returned to the
farmer, according to the newspaper.  The land had been made available to the auto company at a
“throwaway price,” the Times reported.  Farmers originally opposed the land deal, according to the
newspaper.  To contact the reporter on this story:
